&Interned at China Cultural Center Den Haag'}]}, {'title': 'A Comparison study of Musikinstrumenten-museum Berlin and Museum Speelklok', 'date': {'start': {'month': 5, 'day': None, 'year': 2018}, 'end': {'month': 6, 'day': None, 'year': 2018}}, 'description': 'The value of an instrument is to stimulate people’s senses and, in particular, their hearing. Although musical instruments in museums can be considered stationary specimens, unlike other decorative arts, they cannot be isolated from sound. This echoes a general public who seems to view these objects as so associated with music that they cannot be cleanly separated from it. By comparing the musikinstrumenten-museum in Berlin and the Museum Speelklok in Utrecht, this essay explores the following questions: Firstly, how do these two museums present their collections so that visitors can enjoy both a visual and an auditory experience? Secondly, given the Museum of Musical Instruments’ specialised topic, what is the target visitor group for each museum, and how do they fulfil their task? Finally, this essay will conclude with some recommendations on establishing a musical instrument museum for the public.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Tianyi', 'last_name': 'Huang', 'name': None, 'headline': 'MA graduate from Leiden university&18th-century material culture study
